6.14pm India have done really well in the end to drag Australia back from the time they looked like getting anything upwards of 350-360. A sobering thought about the new fielding restrictions and the modern bats: despite an overall excellent display in the end, India still conceded 89 in the last 10

Overall this did look like a slow, slightly two-paced pitch on which timing the ball was not the easiest. Keeping that in mind, Steve Smith was exceptional in his 105 off 93. "Handy little cameo from Mitch," he says now. "Look at the start of the innings we would have settled for this. The pitch was a little bit tacky at the start. It is always nice to get a hundred. This is my favourite place to play, and it has come in a World Cup semi-final. Hopefully we will finish the job in the field."

Ever since India set foot in Australia in November, Smith has scored 921 international runs against them in 10 innings. His lowest against them has been 14 while going for quick second-innings runs on a slow, unyielding pitch in Melbourne

Around Smith, today, Finch battled hard, and once a collapse set in around the 35th over, Watson, Faulkner and Johnson played important little hands to help them over 300. This is the first time this World Cup that India haven't bowled out an opposition. They will need to carry all the confidence and the momentum from having held Australia back if they are to score the highest score in a World Cup semi-final ever. Alan Gardner in some time will be here to bring the chase to you, this is Sidharth Monga saying goodbye
